Barbara Surk, Stephen Castle
https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/18/world/europe/hungary-closes-border-changing-refugees-path.html
With no end in sight to the war in Syria, winter approaching and fears growing that European nations may become less receptive to migrants, thousands have elected to make the risky journey now, while it remains possible.

On Saturday about 600 refugees, mostly Syrians with some Afghans and Iranians, entered Slovenia from Croatia, and were taken to the Austrian frontier at Spielfeld; there, Slovenian police walked groups of them across the border every two hours into Austria, officials said.

In Slovenia, an interior ministry official, Bostjan Sefic, said that 1,800 refugees will be registered at its border with Croatia on Saturday, and most would be taken to reception centers to spend the night.

Mr. Sefic said that Slovenia, which has a population of two million, could process up to 2,500 people a day, and wants to keep the flow at this level to manage it smoothly and efficiently.

But besides worries about Slovenia’s capacity to deal with the movement of migrants, there are also fears about Austria’s ability to cope. Before Hungary closed its Croatian border at midnight Friday, 4,800 migrants who were already in transit arrived in Nickelsdorf, Austria, on Friday from Hungary, while an additional 3,500 were expected to arrive by late Saturday. More were expected on the coming days.

In the last month, 200,000 migrants had passed through Croatia, and almost all had then moved on to Hungary, toward Austria, and then Germany and other welcoming countries to the west and north, migration officials said.

At Slovenia’s border with Austria, Syrians, and other migrants appeared acutely aware of stricter border controls in Austria and Germany in recent days. Many fear that they will get marooned in a Balkan country for days or weeks, or even find that Europe closes the door completely before they can reach Germany or other countries further north.

Advertisement Continue reading the main story

“We wanted to get a visa from the embassy and travel properly, by plane. But it’s not possible,” said Latifa Shaab, a 21-year-old student from the Syrian city of Homs, who had traveled through Turkey, boarded a dinghy that landed in Greece, and made her way through Macedonia, Serbia and Croatia, hoping to reach Sweden.

“From all we heard on the news, this was our last chance to reach Europe, so we left in a hurry,” she said, as she got off the first bus that pulled into Sentlij border crossing between Slovenia and Austria about midday Saturday.

European Refugee and Migrant Crisis

After a half-hour’s rest, and a meal of apples, bread, butter, jam, and chocolate milk for the children, the Slovenian police lined up a group of about 150 people and walked them into Austria, about 700 yards away.

On the Austrian side of the crossing, officers were directing the group, barking over loudspeakers at migrants to form a line.

Hani al-Karaa, a 24-year-old Syrian from the southern city of Dara’a, said he thought that the borders would close sooner or later, just like they did in Lebanon, Jordan and Iraq.

